:::abstract
This article examines the economic accessibility of premium subscriptions for the two leading large language models (LLMs) — ChatGPT (OpenAI) and Claude (Anthropic) — relative to the legal minimum wage in 36 countries across Latin America, Europe, Asia, Africa, and North America. We calculate the percentage of monthly minimum income represented by the USD 20, USD 100, and USD 200 tiers, incorporating the indirect tax burden applicable to digital services (VAT/IGV/GST) and conversion to Peruvian soles (PEN) at the current exchange rate. The results reveal a pronounced asymmetry in access to generative AI tools, constituting a new dimension of the global digital divide.
:::

## Introduction

Generative artificial intelligence systems based on large language models (LLMs), such as ChatGPT developed by OpenAI and Claude developed by Anthropic, have significantly broadened access to productivity, research, and content creation tools. Nevertheless, their premium subscription plans are priced in US dollars with no differentiation for purchasing power parity (PPP), generating an economic accessibility gap between countries with different income levels.

This study aims to quantify, for a sample of 36 countries, what proportion of the legal monthly minimum wage is consumed by Pro and Max subscription tiers on both platforms, also accounting for the impact of indirect taxation on digital services.

