# Key Findings

## 4.1 The basic plan: accessible, but not for everyone

- Accessible — less than 3% of minimum wage: Luxembourg, Australia, Ireland, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Canada, USA high-wage states, South Korea, Japan, Spain, Costa Rica.
- Costly but feasible — between 3% and 10%: Chile, Ecuador, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, Bolivia, Brazil, Poland, Portugal, Bulgaria, Romania, Argentina.
- Practically out of reach — more than 10%: India, Nigeria, Pakistan, Philippines, Vietnam, Ukraine, Nicaragua. Completely impossible in Cuba and Venezuela.

## 4.2 The maximum plan: an extreme luxury

- In Luxembourg, USD 200 is just 6.8% of the minimum wage.
- In Peru, USD 200 equals 60.2% of the minimum wage — more than half of a monthly income.
- In India, USD 200 equals 250% of the minimum wage — 2.5 months of work.
- In Nigeria, a worker would need more than four full months of minimum wage earnings.
- In Venezuela, it would take more than 66 months of minimum wage earnings.

## 4.3 The Peruvian case with 18% IGV

| Plan | Base price | With 18% IGV | In soles | % of min. wage |
| :--- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| ChatGPT Plus / Claude Pro | $20 | $23.60 | S/ 79.98 | 7.1% |
| ChatGPT Pro NEW / Claude Max 5x | $100 | $118.00 | S/ 399.90 | 35.4% |
| ChatGPT Pro max / Claude Max 20x | $200 | $236.00 | S/ 799.80 | 70.8% |
: Peruvian case with IGV {#tbl:peru-case}

:::nota
Peruvian reality. The new USD 100 Pro plan costs S/ 399.90 with IGV in Peru, more than one third of the minimum wage. The maximum USD 200 plan with taxes reaches S/ 799.80, consuming 70.8% of a minimum wage.
:::

:nuevapagina

# Analysis of the OpenAI Announcement (April 9, 2026)

OpenAI is restructuring its subscription plans by introducing a new Pro tier at USD 100/month, positioned between Plus and the maximum Pro tier.

## 5.1 What changes?

1. New intermediate tier: the USD 100/month plan offers 5x more Codex usage than Plus, access to the exclusive Pro model, and unlimited use of Instant and Thinking models.
2. Temporary promotion: until May 31, USD 100 subscribers receive 10x the Codex usage of Plus.
3. The USD 200 plan remains as the fully unlimited option.

## 5.2 What does this mean for the digital divide?

:::nota
The new USD 100 plan does not solve the accessibility problem for low-wage countries. In Peru, USD 100 plus IGV equals S/ 399.90, which exceeds the full minimum wage of Peru, Brazil, Argentina, and Nicaragua.
:::

- For Group A countries, the USD 100 plan is a welcome improvement.
- For Group C countries, the new tier is unaffordable on a minimum wage.
- For Group D-E countries, even the basic plan is not reasonable.

## 5.3 The symmetry with Claude

With this move, ChatGPT now exactly replicates Claude's pricing structure: USD 20 -> USD 100 -> USD 200. Both companies have converged on an identical pricing strategy without accounting for global purchasing power.

:nuevapagina

# Classification: Which Group is Your Country In?

Group A — all subscriptions are accessible: Luxembourg, Australia, Ireland, Germany, USA high-wage states, Canada, France, United Kingdom.

Group B — basic plan is accessible; maximum is a sacrifice: Spain, Japan, South Korea, Poland, Costa Rica, Chile, Uruguay, Portugal, Romania.

Group C — even the basic plan is a significant expense: Peru, Brazil, Argentina, Nicaragua, Ukraine, Vietnam.

Group D — even the basic plan is a luxury: Indonesia, Pakistan.

Group E — completely out of reach: India, Nigeria, Cuba, Venezuela.

:nuevapagina

# Final Reflections

The AI digital divide. These figures reveal a new form of digital inequality. While AI companies headquartered in Silicon Valley set prices with the North American and European markets in mind, billions of people in the Global South are excluded from tools that could enhance their productivity, education, and competitiveness.

Are there solutions?

1. Regional pricing: ChatGPT already offers a Go plan from USD 5/month in Southeast Asia.
2. Educational and NGO plans: subsidized access for students and organizations in low-income countries.
3. Competitive free models: alternatives such as Gemini, Mistral, Llama, and local models offer zero-cost options.
4. Public policy: governments could negotiate national licenses or create AI access funds.

:::nota
Artificial intelligence has the potential to be the great equalizer. But with uniform global pricing, it risks becoming the opposite: a tool that widens the gap between those who can pay and those who cannot. Access to frontier AI should not depend on the country where you were born.
:::

Methodological note: Minimum wages correspond to the gross legal monthly minimum wage in force as of January 1, 2026, per official sources in each country. USD conversions use market exchange rates as of March 1, 2026, unless otherwise stated. PEN conversions use the interbank exchange rate published by the BCRP on April 9, 2026. Tax rates correspond to standard VAT, IGV, or GST applicable to digital services in each jurisdiction. Subscription prices reflect rates published by OpenAI and Anthropic as of April 9, 2026.

:nuevapagina

